00:08:57.140 --> 00:09:00.790
At the heart of this
notion of value at risk

00:09:00.790 --> 00:09:05.350
is this idea of a
statistical order statistic.

00:09:05.350 --> 00:09:08.317
Who here has heard
of order statistics?

00:09:08.317 --> 00:09:10.150
All right, I'm going
to give you 30 seconds.

00:09:10.150 --> 00:09:15.165
The best simple description
of an order statistic.

00:09:15.165 --> 00:09:16.710
PROFESSOR: The
maximum or the minimum

00:09:16.710 --> 00:09:19.600
of a set of observations.

00:09:19.600 --> 00:09:21.230
KENNETH ABBOTT: All right?

00:09:21.230 --> 00:09:23.540
When we talk about
value at risk,

00:09:23.540 --> 00:09:28.420
I want to know the worst
1% of the outcomes.

00:09:28.420 --> 00:09:32.030
And what's cool about
order statistics

00:09:32.030 --> 00:09:34.610
is they're well established
in the literature.

00:09:34.610 --> 00:09:36.840
Pretty well understood.

00:09:36.840 --> 00:09:39.430
And so people are
familiar with it.

00:09:39.430 --> 00:09:42.180
Once we put our toe
into the academic water

00:09:42.180 --> 00:09:44.160
and we start talking
about this notion,

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:46.071
there's a vast
body of literature

00:09:46.071 --> 00:09:47.570
that says this is
how this thing is.

00:09:47.570 --> 00:09:48.460
This is how it pays.

00:09:48.460 --> 00:09:50.680
This is what the
distribution looks like.

00:09:50.680 --> 00:09:55.200
And so we can
estimate these things.

00:09:55.200 --> 00:09:57.830
And so what we're looking
at in value at risk,

00:09:57.830 --> 00:10:03.867
if my distribution of
returns, how much I make.

00:10:03.867 --> 00:10:05.450
In particular, if I
look historically,

00:10:05.450 --> 00:10:06.860
I have a position.

00:10:06.860 --> 00:10:10.630
How much would this position
have earned me over the last n

00:10:10.630 --> 00:10:13.140
days, n weeks, n months.

00:10:13.140 --> 00:10:16.430
If I look at a frequency
distribution of that,

00:10:16.430 --> 00:10:19.690
I'm likely-- don't have to-- I'm
likely to get something that's

00:10:19.690 --> 00:10:20.417
symmetric.

00:10:20.417 --> 00:10:22.250
I'm likely to get
something that's unimodal.

00:10:24.860 --> 00:10:26.610
It may or may not
have fat tails.

00:10:26.610 --> 00:10:29.290
We'll talk about
that a little later.

00:10:29.290 --> 00:10:32.040
If my return distribution
were beautifully symmetric

00:10:32.040 --> 00:10:38.490
and beautifully normal and
independent, then the risk--

00:10:38.490 --> 00:10:40.790
I could measure this
1% order statistic.

00:10:40.790 --> 00:10:46.570
What's the 1% likely worst
case outcome tomorrow?

00:10:46.570 --> 00:10:49.960
I might do that by integrating
the normal function

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:54.150
from negative infinity--
for all intents and purposes

00:10:54.150 --> 00:10:55.640
five or six standard deviations.

00:10:55.640 --> 00:10:59.970
Anyway, from negative
infinity to negative 2.33

00:10:59.970 --> 00:11:01.080
standard deviations.

00:11:01.080 --> 00:11:01.710
Why?

00:11:01.710 --> 00:11:05.250
Because the area under
the curve, that's 0.01.

00:11:05.250 --> 00:11:07.440
Now this is a one-sided
confidence interval

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:09.540
as opposed to a two-sided
confidence integral.

00:11:09.540 --> 00:11:12.060
And this is one of these
things that as an undergrad

00:11:12.060 --> 00:11:14.370
you learn two-sided, and
then the first time someone

00:11:14.370 --> 00:11:15.670
shows you one sided you're
like, wait a minute.

00:11:15.670 --> 00:11:16.212
What is this?

00:11:16.212 --> 00:11:17.336
Than you say, oh, I get it.

00:11:17.336 --> 00:11:18.690
You're just looking at the area.

00:11:18.690 --> 00:11:21.210
I could build a gazillion
two-sided confidence intervals.

00:11:21.210 --> 00:11:23.620
One sided, it's got
to stop at one place.

00:11:23.620 --> 00:11:25.870
All right so this set
of outcomes-- and this

00:11:25.870 --> 00:11:31.480
is standardized-- this is in
standard deviation space--

00:11:31.480 --> 00:11:34.150
negative infinity to 2.33.

