going to be x or
greater, I would go

00:11:42.230 --> 00:11:45.950
to 1.645 standard deviations.

00:11:45.950 --> 00:11:48.120
Because the integral from
negative infinity to 1.645

00:11:48.120 --> 00:11:52.970
standard deviations
is about 0.05.

00:11:52.970 --> 00:11:55.650
It's not just a good
idea, it's the law.

00:11:55.650 --> 00:11:58.560
Does that make sense?

00:11:58.560 --> 00:12:00.602
And again, I'm going to
say assuming the normal.

00:12:00.602 --> 00:12:02.060
That's like the
old economist joke,

00:12:02.060 --> 00:12:04.630
assume a can opener when
he's on a desert island.

00:12:04.630 --> 00:12:05.900
You guys don't know that one.

00:12:05.900 --> 00:12:07.410
I got lots of economics jokes.

00:12:07.410 --> 00:12:10.970
I'll tell them later on
maybe-- or after class.

00:12:10.970 --> 00:12:13.950
If I'm assuming normal
distribution, and that's

00:12:13.950 --> 00:12:16.084
what I'm going to
do, what I want to do

00:12:16.084 --> 00:12:19.600
is I'm going to set this thing
up in a normal distribution

00:12:19.600 --> 00:12:20.140
framework.

00:12:20.140 --> 00:12:24.200
Now doing this approach and
assuming normal distributions,

00:12:24.200 --> 00:12:28.720
I liken it to using Latin.

00:12:28.720 --> 00:12:32.240
Nobody really uses it
anymore but everything we do

00:12:32.240 --> 00:12:33.872
is based upon it.

00:12:33.872 --> 00:12:35.080
So that's our starting point.

00:12:35.080 --> 00:12:37.710
And it's really easy
to teach it this way

00:12:37.710 --> 00:12:39.560
and then we relax
the assumptions

00:12:39.560 --> 00:12:41.210
like so many things in life.

00:12:41.210 --> 00:12:42.880
I teach you the
strict case then we

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:45.630
relax the assumptions to get
to the way it's done now.

00:12:45.630 --> 00:12:48.360
So this makes sense?

00:12:48.360 --> 00:12:48.870
All right.

00:12:48.870 --> 00:12:51.290
So let's get there.

00:12:51.290 --> 00:12:53.670
This is way oversimplified--
but let's say

00:12:53.670 --> 00:12:55.117
I have something like this.

00:12:55.117 --> 00:12:56.700
Who has taken
intermediate statistics?

00:13:01.530 --> 00:13:05.290
We have the notion
of stationarity

00:13:05.290 --> 00:13:06.720
that we talk about all the time.

00:13:06.720 --> 00:13:10.022
The mean and variance
constant is one simplistic way

00:13:10.022 --> 00:13:10.980
of thinking about this.

00:13:10.980 --> 00:13:13.147
Do you have a better way
for me to put that to them?

00:13:13.147 --> 00:13:15.146
Because you know what
their background would be.

00:13:15.146 --> 00:13:15.870
PROFESSOR: No.

00:13:15.870 --> 00:13:16.953
KENNETH ABBOTT: All right.

00:13:16.953 --> 00:13:20.400
Just, mean and
variance are constant.

00:13:20.400 --> 00:13:22.930
When I look at the
time series itself,

00:13:22.930 --> 00:13:26.110
the time series mean and
the time series variance

00:13:26.110 --> 00:13:28.520
are not constant.

00:13:28.520 --> 00:13:30.920
And there also could be other
time series stuff going on.

00:13:30.920 --> 00:13:34.900
There could be seasonality,
there could be autocorrelation.

00:13:34.900 --> 00:13:38.430
This looks something
like a random walk

00:13:38.430 --> 00:13:40.560
but it's not stationary.

00:13:40.560 --> 00:13:43.371
It's hard for me to draw
inference by looking at that

00:13:43.371 --> 00:13:43.870
alone.

00:13:43.870 --> 00:13:45.328
So we want to try
to predict what's

00:13:45.328 --> 00:13:47.460
going to happen in the
future, it's kind of hard.

00:13:47.460 --> 00:13:51.180
And the game, here, that we're
playing, is we want to know

00:13:51.180 --> 00:13:55.510
how much money do I need to
hold to support that position?

00:13:55.510 --> 00:13:58.146
Now, who here has taken
an accounting course?

00:13:58.146 --> 00:14:00.780
All right, word to
the wise-- there's

00:14:00.780 --> 00:14:03.020
two things I tell students
in quant finance programs.

00:14:03.020 --> 00:14:05.686
First of all, I know you have to
take a time series course-- I'm

00:14:05.686 --> 00:14:07.447
sure-- this is MIT.

00:14:07.447 --> 00:14:09.030
If you don't get a
time series course,

00:14:09.030 --> 00:14:11.910
get your money back because
you've got to take time series.

00:14:11.910 --> 00:14:13.540
Accounting is important.

00:14:13.540 --> 00:14:15.500
Accounting is important
because so much

00:14:15.500 --> 00:14:17.350
of what we do, the way
we think about things

00:14:17.350 --> 00:14:18.760
is predicated on the dollars.

00:14:18.760 --> 00:14:22.320
And you need to know how
the dollars are recorded.

00:14:22.320 --> 00:14:22.850
Quick aside.

00:14:28.650 --> 00:14:29.530
Balance sheet.

00:14:29.530 --> 00:14:31.405
I'll give you a 30 second
accounting lecture.

00:14:34.800 --> 00:14:38.230
Assets, what we own.

00:14:38.230 --> 00:14:41.410
Everything we own-- we
have stuff, it's assets.

00:14:41.410 --> 00:14:43.560
We came to that stuff
one of two ways.

00:14:43.560 --> 00:14:46.750
We either pay for it out of our
pocket, or we borrowed money.

00:14:46.750 --> 00:14:48.150
There's no third way.

00:14:48.150 --> 00:14:50.624
So everything we
own, we either paid

00:14:50.624 --> 00:14:52.290
for out of our pocket
or borrowed money.

00:14:52.290 --> 00:14:57.950
The amount we paid for out
of our pocket is the equity.

00:14:57.950 --> 00:15:01.000
The ratio of this to
this is called leverage

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:02.510
among other things.

00:15:02.510 --> 00:15:04.040
All right?

00:15:04.040 --> 00:15:05.400
If I'm this company.

00:15:05.400 --> 00:15:08.230
I have this much
stuff and I bought it

00:15:08.230 --> 00:15:10.630
with this much debt,
and this much equity.

00:15:10.630 --> 00:15:13.760
Again, that's a gross
oversimplification.

00:15:13.760 --> 00:15:16.710
When this gets down to
zero, it's game over.

00:15:16.710 --> 00:15:17.870
Belly up.

00:15:17.870 --> 00:15:19.160
All right?

00:15:19.160 --> 00:15:20.520
Does that make sense?

00:15:20.520 --> 00:15:23.590
Now you've taken a
semester of accounting.

00:15:23.590 --> 00:15:26.050
No, only kidding.

00:15:26.050 --> 00:15:30.970
But it's actually important to
have a grip on how that works.

00:15:30.970 --> 00:15:33.270
Because what we
need to make sure of

00:15:33.270 --> 00:15:36.560
is that if we're going to take
this position and hold it,

00:15:36.560 --> 00:15:40.690
we need to make sure that
with some level of certainty--

00:15:40.690 --> 00:15:43.310
every time we lose
money this gets reduced.

00:15:43.310 --> 00:15:47.040
When this goes down to
zero, I go bankrupt.

00:15:47.040 --> 00:15:48.650
So that's what
we're trying to do.

00:15:48.650 --> 00:15:51.340
We need to protect
this, and we do it

00:15:51.340 --> 00:15:55.220
by knowing how much of
this could move against us.

00:15:55.220 --> 00:15:56.247
Everybody with me?

00:15:56.247 --> 00:15:57.080
Anybody not with me?

00:15:57.080 --> 00:16:00.624
It's OK to have
questions, it really is.

00:16:00.624 --> 00:16:03.540
Excellent.

00:16:03.540 --> 00:16:05.680
All right, so if I do a
frequency distribution

00:16:05.680 --> 00:16:10.980
of this time series, I just
say, show me the frequency

00:16:10.980 --> 00:16:13.270
with which this thing shows.

00:16:13.270 --> 00:16:16.891
I get this thing,
it's kind of trimodal.

00:16:16.891 --> 00:16:17.890
It's all over the place.

00:16:17.890 --> 00:16:19.480
It doesn't tell me anything.

00:16:19.480 --> 00:16:22.200
If I look at the levels--
the frequency distribution,

00:16:22.200 --> 00:16:24.290
the relative frequency
distribution of the levels

00:16:24.290 --> 00:16:26.800
themselves, I don't get
a whole lot of intuition.

00:16:26.800 --> 00:16:29.080
If I go into return
space, which is either

00:16:29.080 --> 00:16:31.440
looking at the log
differences from day to day,

00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:33.340
or the percentage
changes from day to day,

00:16:33.340 --> 00:16:36.030
or perhaps the absolute
changes from day to day--

00:16:36.030 --> 00:16:38.810
it varies from market to market.

00:16:38.810 --> 00:16:41.910
Oh, look, now we're
in familiar territory.

00:16:41.910 --> 00:16:44.260
So what I'm doing
here-- and this

00:16:44.260 --> 00:16:46.350
is why I started out with
a normal distribution

00:16:46.350 --> 00:16:48.640
because this thing is unimodal.

00:16:48.640 --> 00:16:50.310
It's more or less symmetric.

00:16:50.310 --> 00:16:50.960
Right?

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:52.940
Now is it a perfect measure?

00:16:52.940 --> 00:16:55.146
No, because it's
probably got fat tails.

00:16:55.146 --> 00:16:56.520
So it's a little
bit like looking

00:16:56.520 --> 00:16:59.500
for the glasses you lost up on
67th Street down on 59th street

00:16:59.500 --> 00:17:01.140
because there's
more light there.

00:17:01.140 --> 00:17:03.410
But it's a starting point.

00:17:03.410 --> 00:17:09.369
So what I'm saying to you is
once I difference it-- no,

00:17:09.369 --> 00:17:10.660
I won't talk about [INAUDIBLE].

00:17:10.660 --> 00:17:12.099
Once I difference
the timeshares,

00:17:12.099 --> 00:17:14.682
once I take the timeshares and
look at the percentage changes,

00:17:14.682 --> 00:17:17.140
and I look at the frequency
distribution of those changes,

00:17:17.140 --> 00:17:20.109
I get this which is
far more amenable.

00:17:20.109 --> 00:17:22.140
And I can draw
inference from that.

00:17:22.140 --> 00:17:24.950
I can say, ah, now if
this thing is normal,

00:17:24.950 --> 00:17:28.630
then I know that x%
of my observations

00:17:28.630 --> 00:17:30.410
will take place over here.

00:17:30.410 --> 00:17:33.280
Now I can start
drawing inferences.

00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:35.310
And a thing to
keep in mind here,

00:17:35.310 --> 00:17:39.180
one thing we do
constantly in statistics

00:17:39.180 --> 00:17:43.900
is we do parameter estimates.

00:17:43.900 --> 00:17:46.410
And remember, every time
you estimate something

00:17:46.410 --> 00:17:48.480
you estimate it with error.

00:17:48.480 --> 00:17:50.610
I think that maybe the
single most important thing

00:17:50.610 --> 00:17:52.951
I learned when I got
my statistics degree.

00:17:52.951 --> 00:17:54.950
Everything you estimate
you estimate with error.

00:17:54.950 --> 00:17:57.060
People do means,
they say, oh, it's x.

00:17:57.060 --> 00:17:59.712
No, that's the average and
that's an unbiased estimator,

00:17:59.712 --> 00:18:01.670
but guess what, there's
a huge amount of noise.

00:18:01.670 --> 00:18:03.045
And there's a
certain probability

00:18:03.045 --> 00:18:04.400
that you're wrong by x%.

00:18:04.400 --> 00:18:08.110
So every time we come up with a
number, when somebody tells me

00:18:08.110 --> 00:18:11.300
the risk is 10, that means
it's probably not 10,000,

00:18:11.300 --> 00:18:13.532
it's probably not zero.

00:18:13.532 --> 00:18:14.490
Just keep that in mind.

00:18:14.490 --> 00:18:17.200
Just sort of throw that in
on the side for nothing.

00:18:17.200 --> 00:18:20.250
All right, so when I take
the returns of this same time

00:18:20.250 --> 00:18:22.980
series, I get something
that's unimodal, symmetric,

00:18:22.980 --> 00:18:24.560
may or may not have fat tails.

00:18:24.560 --> 00:18:26.750
That has important
implications for whether or not

00:18:26.750 --> 00:18:28.550
my normal distribution
underestimates

00:18:28.550 --> 00:18:30.300
the amount of risk I'm taking.

00:18:30.300 --> 00:18:32.990
Everybody with me on
that more or less?

00:18:32.990 --> 00:18:33.744
Questions?

00:18:33.744 --> 00:18:34.660
Now would be the time.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:41.160
Good enough?

00:18:41.160 --> 00:18:42.660
He's lived this.

00:18:42.660 --> 00:18:44.170
All right.

00:18:44.170 --> 00:18:47.610
So once I have my time series
of returns, which I just

00:18:47.610 --> 00:18:50.170
plotted there, I can
gauge their dispersion

00:18:50.170 --> 00:18:52.382
with this measure
called variance.

00:18:52.382 --> 00:18:53.715
And you guys probably know this.

00:19:01.390 --> 00:19:07.360
Variance, the expected
value of x_i minus x bar-- I

00:19:07.360 --> 00:19:10.960
love these thick
chalks-- squared.

00:19:10.960 --> 00:19:19.640
And it's the sum of x_i minus
x bar squared over n minus 1.

00:19:19.640 --> 00:19:22.680
It's a measure of dispersion.

00:19:22.680 --> 00:19:25.940
Variance has its--
Now, I should say

00:19:25.940 --> 00:19:31.840
that this is sigma squared hat.

00:19:31.840 --> 00:19:32.340
Right?

00:19:32.340 --> 00:19:33.660
Estimate-- parameter estimate.

00:19:33.660 --> 00:19:35.190
Parameter.

00:19:35.190 --> 00:19:37.600
Parameter estimate.

00:19:37.600 --> 00:19:41.990
This is measured with error.

00:19:41.990 --> 00:19:45.616
Anybody here know what the
distribution of this is?

00:19:45.616 --> 00:19:46.750
Anyone?

00:19:46.750 --> 00:19:49.270
$5.

00:19:49.270 --> 00:19:50.530
Close.

00:19:50.530 --> 00:19:51.810
n chi-squared.

00:19:51.810 --> 00:19:52.550
Worth $2.

00:19:52.550 --> 00:19:56.010
Talk to me after class.

00:19:56.010 --> 00:19:57.487
It's a chi-squared distribution.

00:19:57.487 --> 00:19:58.320
What does that mean?

00:19:58.320 --> 00:20:04.177
That means that we know it
can't be 0 or less than 0.

00:20:04.177 --> 00:20:06.510
If you figure out a way to
get variances less than zero,

00:20:06.510 --> 00:20:08.750
let's talk.

00:20:08.750 --> 00:20:10.810
And it's got a long
right tail, but that's

00:20:10.810 --> 00:20:12.020
because this is squared.

00:20:12.020 --> 00:20:14.660
[INAUDIBLE] one
point can move it up.

00:20:14.660 --> 00:20:18.100
Anyway, once I
have my returns, I

00:20:18.100 --> 00:20:20.960
have a measure of the dispersion
of these returns called

00:20:20.960 --> 00:20:22.290
variance.

00:20:22.290 --> 00:20:24.270
I take the square
root of the variance,

00:20:24.270 --> 00:20:28.390
which is the standard
deviation, or the volatility.

00:20:28.390 --> 00:20:29.890
When I'm doing it
with a data set,

00:20:29.890 --> 00:20:32.220
I usually refer to it as
the standard deviation.

00:20:32.220 --> 00:20:36.120
When I'm referring to
the standard deviation

00:20:36.120 --> 00:20:39.500
of the distribution, I usually
call it the standard error.

00:20:39.500 --> 00:20:42.072
Is that a law or is that
just common parlance?

00:20:42.072 --> 00:20:43.052
PROFESSOR: Both.

00:20:43.052 --> 00:20:45.218
The standard error is
typically for something that's

00:20:45.218 --> 00:20:47.264
random, like an estimate.

00:20:47.264 --> 00:20:50.087
Whereas the standard deviation
is more like for sample--

00:20:50.087 --> 00:20:51.170
KENNETH ABBOTT: Empirical.

00:20:51.170 --> 00:20:54.909
See, it's important because
when you first learn this,

00:20:54.909 --> 00:20:55.950
they don't tell you that.

00:20:55.950 --> 00:20:57.420
And they flip them
back and forth.

00:20:57.420 --> 00:20:59.420
And then when you take
the intermediate courses,

00:20:59.420 --> 00:21:01.360
they say, no, don't
use standard deviation

00:21:01.360 --> 00:21:03.460
when you mean standard error.

00:21:03.460 --> 00:21:06.350
And you'll get points off on
your exam for that, right?

00:21:06.350 --> 00:21:09.710
All right, so, the
standard deviation

00:21:09.710 --> 00:21:11.790
is the square root
of the variance,

00:21:11.790 --> 00:21:13.790
also called the volatility.

00:21:13.790 --> 00:21:16.470
In a normal distribution,
1% of the observations

00:21:16.470 --> 00:21:18.775
is outside of 2.33
standard deviations.

00:21:21.330 --> 00:21:27.380
For 95%, it's out past 1.64,
1.645 standard deviations.

00:21:27.380 --> 00:21:28.880
Now you're saying,
wait a minute,

00:21:28.880 --> 00:21:32.000
where did my 1.96 go that
I learned as an undergrad.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:33.740
Two-sided.

00:21:33.740 --> 00:21:37.740
So if I go from the mean
to 1.96 standard deviations

00:21:37.740 --> 00:21:40.570
on either side,
that encompasses 95%

00:21:40.570 --> 00:21:43.000
of the total area of the
integral from negative infinity

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:43.880
to positive infinity.

00:21:43.880 --> 00:21:44.963
Everybody with me on that?

00:21:44.963 --> 00:21:46.560
Does that make sense?

00:21:46.560 --> 00:21:48.020
The two-sided versus one-sided.

00:21:48.020 --> 00:21:49.270
That's confused me.

00:21:49.270 --> 00:21:51.310
When I was your age,
it confused me a lot.

00:21:51.310 --> 00:21:53.950
But I got there.

00:21:53.950 --> 00:21:56.960
All right so this
is how we do it.

00:21:56.960 --> 00:22:00.092
Excel functions are VAR and--
you don't need to know that.

00:22:00.092 --> 00:22:02.300
All right, so in this case,
I estimating the variance

00:22:02.300 --> 00:22:04.340
of this particular time series.

00:22:04.340 --> 00:22:06.920
I took the standard deviation
by taking the square root

00:22:06.920 --> 00:22:09.040
of the variance.

00:22:09.040 --> 00:22:10.610
It's in percentages.

00:22:10.610 --> 00:22:12.990
When you do this, I tell
you, it's like physics,

00:22:12.990 --> 00:22:16.737
your units will screw
you up every time.

00:22:16.737 --> 00:22:17.570
What am I measuring?

00:22:17.570 --> 00:22:18.740
What are my units?

00:22:18.740 --> 00:22:20.130
I still make units mistakes.

00:22:20.130 --> 00:22:20.890
I want you to know that.

00:22:20.890 --> 00:22:21.880
And I'm in this
business 30 years.

00:22:21.880 --> 00:22:23.400
I still make units mistakes.

00:22:23.400 --> 00:22:24.950
Just like physics.

00:22:24.950 --> 00:22:26.740
I'm in percentage
change space, so I

00:22:26.740 --> 00:22:28.573
want to talk in terms
of percentage changes.

00:22:28.573 --> 00:22:31.820
The standard deviation is
1.8% of that time series

00:22:31.820 --> 00:22:33.090
I showed you.

00:22:33.090 --> 00:22:36.410
So 2.33 standard deviations
times the standard deviation

00:22:36.410 --> 00:22:38.720
is about 4.2%.

00:22:38.720 --> 00:22:46.280
What that says, given this data
set-- one time series-- I'm

00:22:46.280 --> 00:22:50.430
saying, I expect to
lose, on any given day,

00:22:50.430 --> 00:22:54.540
if I have that position,
99% of the time I'm going

00:22:54.540 --> 00:22:58.240
to lose 4.2% of it or less.

00:23:00.840 --> 00:23:01.472
Very important.

00:23:01.472 --> 00:23:02.180
Think about that.

00:23:02.180 --> 00:23:04.750
Is that clear?

00:23:04.750 --> 00:23:06.960
That's how I get there.

00:23:06.960 --> 00:23:09.880
I'm making a statement about
the probability of loss.

00:23:09.880 --> 00:23:12.490
I'm saying there's
a 1% probability,

00:23:12.490 --> 00:23:19.910
for that particular time
series-- which is-- all right?

00:23:19.910 --> 00:23:21.530
If this is my
historical data set

00:23:21.530 --> 00:23:24.640
and it's my only historical
data set, and I own this,

00:23:24.640 --> 00:23:28.812
tomorrow I may be 4.2%
lighter than I was today

00:23:28.812 --> 00:23:30.520
because the market
could move against me.

00:23:30.520 --> 00:23:34.930
And I'm 99% sure, if the
future's like the past,

00:23:34.930 --> 00:23:40.240
that my loss tomorrow is
going to be 4.2% or less.

00:23:40.240 --> 00:23:42.670
That's VaR.

00:23:42.670 --> 00:23:45.860
Simplest case, assuming
normal distribution,

00:23:45.860 --> 00:23:50.500
single asset, not fixed income.

00:23:50.500 --> 00:23:51.290
Yes, no?

00:23:51.290 --> 00:23:52.180
Questions, comments?

00:23:52.180 --> 00:23:58.779
AUDIENCE: Yes, [INAUDIBLE]
positive and [INAUDIBLE].

00:23:58.779 --> 00:23:59.820
KENNETH ABBOTT: Yes, yes.

00:23:59.820 --> 00:24:02.960
Assuming my distribution
is symmetric.

00:24:02.960 --> 00:24:08.210
Now that's the right
assumption to point out.

00:24:08.210 --> 00:24:11.110
Because in the real world,
it may not be symmetric.

00:24:11.110 --> 00:24:13.580
And when we go into
historical simulation,

00:24:13.580 --> 00:24:15.081
we use empirical
distributions where

00:24:15.081 --> 00:24:17.163
we don't care if it's
symmetric because we're only

00:24:17.163 --> 00:24:18.310
looking at the downside.

00:24:18.310 --> 00:24:21.390
And whether I'm long
or short, I might

00:24:21.390 --> 00:24:24.337
care about the downside
or the putative upside.

00:24:24.337 --> 00:24:26.170
Because I'm short, and
I care about how much

00:24:26.170 --> 00:24:27.220
is going to move up.

00:24:27.220 --> 00:24:27.750
Make sense?

00:24:27.750 --> 00:24:29.720
That's the right
question to ask.

00:24:29.720 --> 00:24:30.350
Yes?

00:24:30.350 --> 00:24:34.172
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] if you're
doing it for upside as well?

00:24:34.172 --> 00:24:35.005
KENNETH ABBOTT: Yes.

00:24:35.005 --> 00:24:36.000
AUDIENCE: Could it
just be the same thing?

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:36.833
KENNETH ABBOTT: Yes.

00:24:36.833 --> 00:24:38.970
In fact, in this case,
in what we're doing here

00:24:38.970 --> 00:24:41.380
of variance/covariance
or closed form VaR,

00:24:41.380 --> 00:24:43.954
it's for long or short.

00:24:43.954 --> 00:24:45.870
But getting your signs
right, I'm telling you,

00:24:45.870 --> 00:24:47.380
it's like physics.

00:24:47.380 --> 00:24:49.940
I still make that mistake.

00:24:49.940 --> 00:24:50.688
Yes?

00:24:50.688 --> 00:24:53.178
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] symmetric.

00:24:53.178 --> 00:24:55.600
Do you guys still use
this process to say, OK--

00:24:55.600 --> 00:24:59.300
KENNETH ABBOTT: I use it
all the time as a heuristic.

00:24:59.300 --> 00:25:00.290
All right?

00:25:00.290 --> 00:25:05.530
Because let's say I've got-- and
that's a very good question--

00:25:05.530 --> 00:25:09.260
let's say I've got five
years worth of data

00:25:09.260 --> 00:25:13.330
and I don't have time to
do an empirical estimate.

00:25:13.330 --> 00:25:17.090
It could be lopsided.

00:25:17.090 --> 00:25:19.910
If you tell me a two
standard deviation move

00:25:19.910 --> 00:25:22.880
is x, that means
something to me.

00:25:22.880 --> 00:25:25.230
Now, there's a
problem with that.

00:25:25.230 --> 00:25:28.432
And the problem is that
people extrapolate that.

00:25:28.432 --> 00:25:30.890
Sometimes people talk to me
and, oh, it's an eight standard

00:25:30.890 --> 00:25:32.610
deviation move.

00:25:32.610 --> 00:25:34.769
Eight standard deviation
moves don't happen.

00:25:34.769 --> 00:25:36.935
I don't think we've seen
an eight standard deviation

00:25:36.935 --> 00:25:40.120
move in the Cenozoic era.

00:25:40.120 --> 00:25:43.020
It just doesn't happen.

00:25:43.020 --> 00:25:45.500
Three standard deviation--
you will see a three standard

00:25:45.500 --> 00:25:50.160
deviation move once every
10,000 observations.

00:25:50.160 --> 00:25:53.874
Now, I learned this
the hard way by just,

00:25:53.874 --> 00:25:55.540
see how many times
do I have to do this?

00:25:55.540 --> 00:25:57.789
And then I looked it up in
the table, oh, I was right.

00:26:00.400 --> 00:26:02.950
When we oversimplify, and
start to talk about everything

00:26:02.950 --> 00:26:04.491
in terms of that
normal distribution,

00:26:04.491 --> 00:26:07.100
we really just lose
our grip on reality.

00:26:07.100 --> 00:26:10.020
But I use it as a
heuristic all the time.

00:26:10.020 --> 00:26:12.457
I'll do it even now,
and I know better.

00:26:12.457 --> 00:26:14.290
But I'll go, what's two
standard deviations?

00:26:14.290 --> 00:26:15.664
What's three
standard deviations?

00:26:15.664 --> 00:26:22.270
Because by and large-- and I
still do this, I get my data

00:26:22.270 --> 00:26:25.560
and I line it up and I do
frequency distributions.

00:26:25.560 --> 00:26:29.510
Hold on, I do this all
the time with my data.

00:26:29.510 --> 00:26:30.660
Is it symmetric?

00:26:30.660 --> 00:26:32.050
Is it fat tailed?

00:26:32.050 --> 00:26:33.000
Is it unimodal?

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:35.435
So that's a very good question.

00:26:35.435 --> 00:26:36.270
Any other questions?

00:26:36.270 --> 00:26:37.770
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
have we talked

00:26:37.770 --> 00:26:39.830
about the [? standard t ?]
distribution?

00:26:39.830 --> 00:26:43.511
PROFESSOR: We Introduced
it in the last lecture.

00:26:43.511 --> 00:26:48.540
And the problems set this
week does relate to that.

00:26:48.540 --> 00:26:51.180
KENNETH ABBOTT: All
right, perfect lead-in.

00:26:51.180 --> 00:26:54.090
So the statement I made,
it's 1% of the time

00:26:54.090 --> 00:26:59.340
I'd expect to lose more than
4.2 pesos on 100 peso position.

00:26:59.340 --> 00:27:03.870
That's my inferential statement.

00:27:03.870 --> 00:27:08.020
In fact, over the
same time period

00:27:08.020 --> 00:27:14.760
I lost 4.2% 1.5% of the time
instead of 1% of the time.

00:27:14.760 --> 00:27:19.220
What that tells me, what that
suggests to me, is my data set

00:27:19.220 --> 00:27:20.860
has fat tails.

00:27:20.860 --> 00:27:24.820
What that means is the
likelihood of a loss--

00:27:24.820 --> 00:27:27.340
a simple way of thinking
about it [INAUDIBLE] care

00:27:27.340 --> 00:27:30.590
whether what that means
in a metaphysical sense,

00:27:30.590 --> 00:27:32.410
a way to interpret it.

00:27:32.410 --> 00:27:35.290
The likelihood of
a loss is greater

00:27:35.290 --> 00:27:38.491
than would be implied by
the normal distribution.

00:27:38.491 --> 00:27:38.990
All right?

00:27:38.990 --> 00:27:41.330
So when you hear
people say fat tails,

00:27:41.330 --> 00:27:43.870
generally, that's what
they're talking about.

00:27:43.870 --> 00:27:46.370
There are different ways you
could interpret that statement,

00:27:46.370 --> 00:27:49.860
but when somebody is talking
about a financial time series,

00:27:49.860 --> 00:27:51.252
it has fat tails.

00:27:51.252 --> 00:27:52.960
Roughly 3/4 of your
financial time series

00:27:52.960 --> 00:27:53.829
will have fat tails.

00:27:53.829 --> 00:27:55.620
They will also have
time series properties,

00:27:55.620 --> 00:27:57.110
they won't be true random walks.

00:27:57.110 --> 00:27:59.080
True random walks
says that I don't

00:27:59.080 --> 00:28:01.840
know whether it's going to go
up or down based on the data

00:28:01.840 --> 00:28:03.150
I have.

00:28:03.150 --> 00:28:05.659
The time series has no memory.

00:28:05.659 --> 00:28:07.950
When we start introducing
time series properties, which

00:28:07.950 --> 00:28:12.950
many financial time series
have, then there's seasonality,

00:28:12.950 --> 00:28:15.130
there's mean reversion,
there's all kinds

00:28:15.130 --> 00:28:17.130
of other stuff, other
ways that we have to think

00:28:17.130 --> 00:28:19.250
about modeling the data.

00:28:19.250 --> 00:28:20.764
Make sense?

00:28:20.764 --> 00:28:25.930
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] higher
standard deviation than

00:28:25.930 --> 00:28:26.430
[INAUDIBLE].

00:28:26.430 --> 00:28:28.410
KENNETH ABBOTT:
Say it once again.

00:28:28.410 --> 00:28:30.605
AUDIENCE: Better
yield, does it mean

00:28:30.605 --> 00:28:33.030
that we have a higher standard
deviation than [INAUDIBLE]?

00:28:33.030 --> 00:28:33.570
KENNETH ABBOTT: No.

00:28:33.570 --> 00:28:35.611
The standard deviation is
the standard deviation.

00:28:37.820 --> 00:28:42.100
No matter what I do, this is
standard deviation, that's it.

00:28:42.100 --> 00:28:44.790
Don't have a higher
standard deviation.

00:28:44.790 --> 00:28:46.730
But the likelihood
of-- the put it

00:28:46.730 --> 00:28:52.740
this way-- the likelihood
of a move of 2.33

00:28:52.740 --> 00:28:54.860
standard deviations
is more than 1%.

00:28:57.890 --> 00:28:59.670
That's the way I think of it.

00:28:59.670 --> 00:29:02.585
Make sense?

00:29:02.585 --> 00:29:05.091
AUDIENCE: Is there any way
for you to [INAUDIBLE] to--

00:29:05.091 --> 00:29:05.966
KENNETH ABBOTT: What?

00:29:05.966 --> 00:29:07.340
AUDIENCE: Sorry,
is there any way

00:29:07.340 --> 00:29:09.690
to put into that graph what
a fatter tail looks like?

00:29:09.690 --> 00:29:11.890
KENNETH ABBOTT: Oh,
well, be patient.

00:29:11.890 --> 00:29:13.365
If we have time.

00:29:13.365 --> 00:29:14.740
In fact, we do
that all the time.

00:29:14.740 --> 00:29:16.700
And one of our
techniques doesn't care.

00:29:16.700 --> 00:29:18.290
It goes to the
empirical distribution.

00:29:18.290 --> 00:29:20.620
So it captures the
fat tails completely.

00:29:20.620 --> 00:29:25.210
In fact, the homework
assignment which I usually

00:29:25.210 --> 00:29:27.010
precede this lecture
by has people

00:29:27.010 --> 00:29:28.740
graphing all kinds
of distributions

00:29:28.740 --> 00:29:31.384
to see what these
things look like.

00:29:31.384 --> 00:29:32.550
We won't have time for that.

00:29:32.550 --> 00:29:35.130
But if you have questions,
send them to me.

00:29:35.130 --> 00:29:37.520
I'll send you some stuff
to read about this.

00:29:37.520 --> 00:29:39.228
All right, so now you
know one asset VaR,

00:29:39.228 --> 00:29:41.240
now you're qualified to
go work for a big bank.

00:29:41.240 --> 00:29:42.470
All right?

00:29:42.470 --> 00:29:44.530
Get your data,
calculate returns.

00:29:44.530 --> 00:29:50.100
Now I usually put in step 2b,
graph your data and look at it.

00:29:50.100 --> 00:29:50.630
All right?

00:29:50.630 --> 00:29:54.350
Because everybody's
data has dirt in it.

00:29:54.350 --> 00:29:55.410
Don't trust anyone else.

00:29:55.410 --> 00:29:56.850
If you're going
to get fired, get

00:29:56.850 --> 00:29:58.266
fired for being
incompetent, don't

00:29:58.266 --> 00:30:01.310
get fired for using
someone else's bad data.

00:30:01.310 --> 00:30:02.260
Don't trust anyone.

00:30:02.260 --> 00:30:05.100
My mother gives me data,
Mom, I'm graphing it.

00:30:05.100 --> 00:30:09.290
Because I think you let
some poop slip into my data.

00:30:09.290 --> 00:30:15.430
Mother Teresa could come to me
with a thumb drive: "Ken, S&amp;P

00:30:15.430 --> 00:30:17.316
500."

00:30:17.316 --> 00:30:18.190
Sorry, Mother Teresa.

00:30:18.190 --> 00:30:20.500
I'm graphing it before I use it.

00:30:20.500 --> 00:30:21.070
All right?

00:30:21.070 --> 00:30:23.236
So I don't want to say that
this is usually in here.

00:30:23.236 --> 00:30:24.855
We do extensive error testing.

00:30:24.855 --> 00:30:27.670
Because there could be bad data,
there could be missing data.

00:30:27.670 --> 00:30:31.210
And missing data is a whole
other lecture that I give.

00:30:31.210 --> 00:30:32.723
You might be shocked
at [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:36.590 --> 00:30:40.590
So for one asset VaR, get my
data, create my return series.

00:30:40.590 --> 00:30:42.010
Percentage changes, log changes.

00:30:42.010 --> 00:30:43.720
Sometimes that's
absolute differences.

00:30:43.720 --> 00:30:46.053
Take the variance, take the
square root of the variance,

00:30:46.053 --> 00:30:47.100
multiply by 2.33.

00:30:47.100 --> 00:30:47.800
Done and dusted.

00:30:47.800 --> 00:30:49.990
Go home, take your
shoes off, relax.

00:30:53.730 --> 00:30:54.640
OK.

00:30:54.640 --> 00:30:57.290
Percentage changes
versus log changes.

00:30:57.290 --> 00:31:00.530
For all intents and purposes,
it doesn't really matter

00:31:00.530 --> 00:31:04.161
and I will often use
one or the other.

00:31:04.161 --> 00:31:19.030
The way I think about
this-- all right,

00:31:19.030 --> 00:31:21.110
there'll be a little
bit of bias at the ends.

00:31:21.110 --> 00:31:23.240
But for the overwhelming
bulk of the observations

00:31:23.240 --> 00:31:25.800
whether you use percentage
changes or log changes

00:31:25.800 --> 00:31:27.200
doesn't matter.

00:31:27.200 --> 00:31:30.250
Generally, even though I
know the data is closer

00:31:30.250 --> 00:31:32.850
to log-normally distributed
than normally distributed,

00:31:32.850 --> 00:31:36.082
I'll use percentage changes
just because it's easier.

00:31:36.082 --> 00:31:37.790
Why would we use
log-normal distribution?

00:31:37.790 --> 00:31:42.587
Well, when we're
doing simulation,

00:31:42.587 --> 00:31:44.920
the log-normal distribution
has this very nifty property

00:31:44.920 --> 00:31:48.430
of keeping your yields
from going negative.

00:31:48.430 --> 00:31:50.440
But, even that-- I
can call that into

00:31:50.440 --> 00:31:52.510
question because
there are instances

00:31:52.510 --> 00:31:54.436
of yields going negative.

00:31:54.436 --> 00:31:55.670
It's happened.

00:31:55.670 --> 00:31:58.180
Doesn't happen a
lot, but it happens.

00:31:58.180 --> 00:31:58.824
All right.

00:31:58.824 --> 00:32:00.240
So I talked about
bad data, talked

00:32:00.240 --> 00:32:02.420
about one-sided
versus two-sided.

00:32:02.420 --> 00:32:05.727
I'll talk about longs and shorts
a little bit later when we

00:32:05.727 --> 00:32:06.810
we're talking multi-asset.

00:32:11.040 --> 00:32:14.280
I'm going to cover a
fixed income piece.

00:32:14.280 --> 00:32:17.410
We use this thing called a PV01
because what I measure in fixed

00:32:17.410 --> 00:32:18.730
income markets isn't a price.

00:32:18.730 --> 00:32:20.290
I usually measure a yield.

00:32:20.290 --> 00:32:23.592
I have to get from a change
of yield to a change of price.

00:32:23.592 --> 00:32:25.050
Hmm, sounds like
a Jacobian, right?

00:32:25.050 --> 00:32:27.990
With kind of a poor
man's Jacobian.

00:32:27.990 --> 00:32:30.560
It's a measure that
captures the fact

00:32:30.560 --> 00:32:36.340
that my price-yield
relationship--

00:32:36.340 --> 00:32:40.180
price, yield-- is non-linear.

00:32:40.180 --> 00:32:44.700
For any small approximation
I look at the tangent.

00:32:44.700 --> 00:32:49.020
And I use my PV01 which has
a similar notion to duration,

00:32:49.020 --> 00:32:51.390
but PV01 is a little
more practical.

00:32:51.390 --> 00:32:53.019
The slope of that
tells me how much

00:32:53.019 --> 00:32:55.060
my price will change for
a given change of yield.

00:32:55.060 --> 00:32:55.690
See, there it is.

00:32:55.690 --> 00:32:57.280
You knew you were going to
use the calculus, right?

00:32:57.280 --> 00:32:58.730
You're always
using the calculus.

00:32:58.730 --> 00:33:01.280
You can't escape it.

00:33:01.280 --> 00:33:03.380
But the price-yield
line is non-linear.

00:33:03.380 --> 00:33:05.710
But for all intents and
purposes, what I'm doing is

00:33:05.710 --> 00:33:07.940
I'm shifting the
price-yield relationship--

00:33:07.940 --> 00:33:10.120
I'm shifting my yield
change into price change

00:33:10.120 --> 00:33:14.560
by multiplying my yield
change by my PV01 which

00:33:14.560 --> 00:33:21.131
is my price sensitivity to
1/100th percent move in yields.

00:33:21.131 --> 00:33:22.380
Think about that for a second.

00:33:22.380 --> 00:33:23.880
We don't have time
to-- I would love

00:33:23.880 --> 00:33:26.270
to spend an hour on this,
and about trading strategies,

00:33:26.270 --> 00:33:28.524
and about bull steepeners
and bear steepeners

00:33:28.524 --> 00:33:30.690
and barbell trades, but we
don't have time for that.

00:33:30.690 --> 00:33:35.090
Suffice to say if I'm
measuring yields the thing

00:33:35.090 --> 00:33:41.960
is going to trade as a 789
or a 622 or a 401 yield.

00:33:41.960 --> 00:33:43.880
How do I get that in
the change in price?

00:33:43.880 --> 00:33:46.046
Because I can't tell my
boss, hey, I had a good day.

00:33:46.046 --> 00:33:48.360
I bought it at 402
and sold it at 401.

00:33:48.360 --> 00:33:50.170
No, how much money did you make?

00:33:50.170 --> 00:33:51.920
Yield to coffee break
yield to lunch time,

00:33:51.920 --> 00:33:53.880
yield to go home
at the end of day.

00:33:53.880 --> 00:33:56.710
How do I get from change in
yield to change in price?

00:33:56.710 --> 00:33:58.330
Usually PV01.

00:33:58.330 --> 00:34:00.446
I could use duration.

00:34:00.446 --> 00:34:02.820
Bond traders who think in
terms of yield to coffee break,

00:34:02.820 --> 00:34:04.515
yield to lunch time, yield to
go home at the end of the day

00:34:04.515 --> 00:34:05.525
typically think
in terms of PV01.

00:34:05.525 --> 00:34:07.130
Do you agree with
that statement?

00:34:07.130 --> 00:34:08.420
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:34:08.420 --> 00:34:10.503
KENNETH ABBOTT: How often
on the fixed income desk

00:34:10.503 --> 00:34:11.957
did you use duration measures?

00:34:11.957 --> 00:34:15.880
AUDIENCE: Well,
actually, [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:15.880 --> 00:34:18.070
KENNETH ABBOTT: Because
of the investor horizon?

00:34:18.070 --> 00:34:20.761
OK, the insurance companies.

00:34:20.761 --> 00:34:23.219
Very important point I want to
reach here as a quick aside.

00:34:23.219 --> 00:34:25.389
You're going to hear
this notion of PV01,

00:34:25.389 --> 00:34:28.239
which is called PVBP or DV01.

00:34:28.239 --> 00:34:31.460
That's the price sensitivity
to a one basis point move.

00:34:31.460 --> 00:34:35.840
One basis point is 1/100th
of a percent in yield.

00:34:35.840 --> 00:34:41.360
Duration is the half life,
essentially, of my cash flow.

00:34:41.360 --> 00:34:44.870
What's the weighted expected
time to owe my cash flows?

00:34:44.870 --> 00:34:51.070
If my duration is 7.9 years,
my PV01 is probably about $790

00:34:51.070 --> 00:34:53.500
per million.

00:34:53.500 --> 00:34:56.069
In terms of significant digits,
they're roughly the same

00:34:56.069 --> 00:34:58.610
but they have different meanings
and the units are different.

00:34:58.610 --> 00:35:03.530
Duration is measured in yield,
PV01 is measured in dollars.

00:35:03.530 --> 00:35:06.280
In bond space I
typically think in PV01.

00:35:06.280 --> 00:35:08.580
If I'm selling to
long term investors

00:35:08.580 --> 00:35:11.530
they have particular demands
because they've got cash flow

00:35:11.530 --> 00:35:13.310
payments they have to hedge.

00:35:13.310 --> 00:35:15.740
So they may think of it
in terms of duration.

00:35:15.740 --> 00:35:20.560
For our purposes, we're
talking DV01 or PV01 or PVBP,

00:35:20.560 --> 00:35:23.050
those three terms
more or less equal.

00:35:23.050 --> 00:35:23.710
Make sense?

00:35:23.710 --> 00:35:24.553
Yes?

00:35:24.553 --> 00:35:27.018
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] in
terms of [INAUDIBLE] versus

00:35:27.018 --> 00:35:28.259
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:35:28.259 --> 00:35:29.300
KENNETH ABBOTT: We could.

00:35:29.300 --> 00:35:32.850
In some instances, in
some areas and options

00:35:32.850 --> 00:35:34.800
we might look at
an overall 1% move.

00:35:34.800 --> 00:35:38.000
But we have to look at
what trades in the market.

