with everything.

00:36:57.850 --> 00:36:59.555
All of the models fell apart.

00:36:59.555 --> 00:37:01.260
There were appendices
to every chapter

00:37:01.260 --> 00:37:04.610
on how you have to change this
model to address inflation.

00:37:04.610 --> 00:37:07.500
And then inflation went away
and everything was better.

00:37:07.500 --> 00:37:09.140
But this may not go away.

00:37:09.140 --> 00:37:10.650
I've got two components here.

00:37:10.650 --> 00:37:17.530
If the yield is 6%, I might
have a 450 treasury rate and 150

00:37:17.530 --> 00:37:19.820
basis point credit spread.

00:37:19.820 --> 00:37:22.430
The credit spread reflects
the probability of default.

00:37:22.430 --> 00:37:24.770
And I don't want to get into
measures of risk neutrality

00:37:24.770 --> 00:37:25.830
here.

00:37:25.830 --> 00:37:29.840
But if I'm an issuer and I
have a chance of default,

00:37:29.840 --> 00:37:33.010
I have to pay my investors more.

00:37:33.010 --> 00:37:40.767
Usually when we
measure sensitivity

00:37:40.767 --> 00:37:42.600
we talk about that
credit spread sensitivity

00:37:42.600 --> 00:37:45.340
and the risk-free sensitivity.

00:37:45.340 --> 00:37:47.492
We say, well, how could
they possibly be different?

00:37:47.492 --> 00:37:49.200
And I don't want to
get into detail here,

00:37:49.200 --> 00:37:52.380
but the notion is, when credit
spreads start getting high,

00:37:52.380 --> 00:37:56.964
it implies a higher
probability of default.

00:37:56.964 --> 00:37:59.380
You have to think about credit
spread sensitivity a little

00:37:59.380 --> 00:37:59.750
differently.

00:37:59.750 --> 00:38:01.541
Because when you get
to 1,000 basis points,

00:38:01.541 --> 00:38:03.450
1,500 basis points
credit spread,

00:38:03.450 --> 00:38:04.920
it's a high
probability of default.

00:38:04.920 --> 00:38:07.230
And your credit models
will think differently.

00:38:07.230 --> 00:38:09.270
Your credit models will
say, ah, that means

00:38:09.270 --> 00:38:11.260
I'm not going to get
my next three payments.

00:38:11.260 --> 00:38:13.690
There's an expected, there's
a probability of default,

00:38:13.690 --> 00:38:16.400
there's a loss given default,
and there's recovery.

00:38:16.400 --> 00:38:18.660
A bunch of other stochastic
measures come into play.

00:38:18.660 --> 00:38:20.180
I don't want to spend any more
time on it because it's just

00:38:20.180 --> 00:38:21.820
going to confuse you now.

00:38:21.820 --> 00:38:25.720
Suffice to say we have
these yields and yields

00:38:25.720 --> 00:38:29.390
are composed of risk-free
rates and credit spreads.

00:38:29.390 --> 00:38:31.597
And I apologize for
rushing through that,

00:38:31.597 --> 00:38:32.930
but we don't have time to do it.

00:38:36.290 --> 00:38:38.450
Typically you have
more than one asset.

00:38:38.450 --> 00:38:43.030
So in this framework where I
take 2.33 standard deviations

00:38:43.030 --> 00:38:46.370
times my dollar investment,
or my renminbi investment

00:38:46.370 --> 00:38:47.705
or my sterling investment.

00:38:50.520 --> 00:38:52.060
That example was with one asset.

00:38:52.060 --> 00:38:55.010
If I want to expand
this, I can expand

00:38:55.010 --> 00:39:01.276
this using this notion of
covariance and correlation.

00:39:01.276 --> 00:39:03.650
You guys covered correlation
and covariance at some point

00:39:03.650 --> 00:39:04.940
in your careers?

00:39:04.940 --> 00:39:05.780
Yes, no?

00:39:05.780 --> 00:39:08.460
All right?

00:39:08.460 --> 00:39:12.820
Both of them measure the way one
asset moves vis--vis another

00:39:12.820 --> 00:39:14.310
asset.

00:39:14.310 --> 00:39:19.040
Correlation is scaled between
negative 1 and positive 1.

00:39:19.040 --> 00:39:23.280
So I think of correlation
as an index of linearity.

00:39:23.280 --> 00:39:24.650
Covariance is not scaled.

00:39:24.650 --> 00:39:26.290
I'll give you an example of the
difference between covariance

00:39:26.290 --> 00:39:27.240
and correlation.

00:39:27.240 --> 00:39:31.430
What if I have 50 years
of data on crop yields

00:39:31.430 --> 00:39:35.900
and that same 50 years of data
on tons of fertilizer used?

00:39:35.900 --> 00:39:38.550
I would expect a
positive correlation

00:39:38.550 --> 00:39:41.709
between tons of fertilizer
used and crop yields.

00:39:41.709 --> 00:39:43.750
So the correlation would
exist between negative 1

00:39:43.750 --> 00:39:45.360
and positive 1.

00:39:45.360 --> 00:39:47.072
The covariance
could be any number,

00:39:47.072 --> 00:39:48.780
and that covariance
will change depending

00:39:48.780 --> 00:39:50.670
on whether I measure
my fertilizer

00:39:50.670 --> 00:39:56.950
in tons, or in pounds, or
in ounces, or in kilos.

00:39:56.950 --> 00:39:59.500
The correlation will
always be exactly the same.

00:39:59.500 --> 00:40:03.630
The linear relationship is
captured by the correlation.

00:40:03.630 --> 00:40:08.440
But the units-- in
covariance, the units count.

00:40:08.440 --> 00:40:14.100
If I have covariance--
here it is.

00:40:23.050 --> 00:40:25.450
Covariance matrices
are symmetric.

00:40:25.450 --> 00:40:28.940
They have the variance
along the diagonal.

00:40:28.940 --> 00:40:31.500
And the covariance is
on the off-diagonal.

00:40:31.500 --> 00:40:33.980
Which is to say that the
variance is the covariance

00:40:33.980 --> 00:40:36.510
of an item with itself.

00:40:36.510 --> 00:40:39.750
The correlation
matrix, also symmetric,

00:40:39.750 --> 00:40:44.800
is the same thing scaled,
with correlations,

00:40:44.800 --> 00:40:47.900
where the diagonal is 1.0.

00:40:47.900 --> 00:40:51.430
If I have covariance--
because correlation

00:40:51.430 --> 00:41:01.560
is covariance--
covariance divided

00:41:01.560 --> 00:41:04.100
by the product of the
standard deviations

00:41:04.100 --> 00:41:07.650
gets me-- sorry--
correlation hat.

00:41:12.280 --> 00:41:15.410
This is like the
apostrophe in French.

00:41:15.410 --> 00:41:16.980
You forget it all the time.

00:41:16.980 --> 00:41:20.060
But the one time you really
need it, you won't do it

00:41:20.060 --> 00:41:22.820
and you'll be in trouble.

00:41:22.820 --> 00:41:25.650
If you have the covariances,
you can get to the correlations.

00:41:25.650 --> 00:41:27.090
If you have the
correlations, you

00:41:27.090 --> 00:41:29.700
can't get to the covariances
unless you know the variances.

00:41:29.700 --> 00:41:31.750
That's a classic
mid-term question.

00:41:31.750 --> 00:41:37.300
I give that almost-- not every
year, maybe every other year.

00:41:37.300 --> 00:41:39.350
Don't have time to spend
much more time on it.

00:41:39.350 --> 00:41:41.500
Suffice to say this
measure of covariance

00:41:41.500 --> 00:41:43.870
says when x is a certain
distance from its mean,

00:41:43.870 --> 00:41:47.131
how far is y from its mean
and in what direction?

00:41:47.131 --> 00:41:47.630
Yes?

00:41:50.520 --> 00:41:52.320
Now this is just a
little empirical stuff

00:41:52.320 --> 00:41:54.400
because I'm not as
clever as you guys.

00:41:54.400 --> 00:41:56.530
And I don't trust anyone.

00:41:56.530 --> 00:42:00.550
I read it in the textbook,
I don't trust anyone.

00:42:00.550 --> 00:42:03.707
a, b, here's a plus b.

00:42:03.707 --> 00:42:06.040
Variance of a plus b is
variance of a plus variance of b

00:42:06.040 --> 00:42:07.340
plus 2 times covariance a b.

00:42:07.340 --> 00:42:10.180
It's not just a good
idea, it's the law.

00:42:10.180 --> 00:42:12.350
I saw it in a thousand
statistics textbooks,

00:42:12.350 --> 00:42:13.762
I tested it anyway.

00:42:13.762 --> 00:42:15.220
Because if I want
to get fired, I'm

00:42:15.220 --> 00:42:17.170
going to get fired for
making my own mistake,

00:42:17.170 --> 00:42:18.590
not making someone
else's mistake.

00:42:18.590 --> 00:42:20.280
I do this all the time.

00:42:20.280 --> 00:42:22.610
And I just prove it
empirically here.

00:42:22.610 --> 00:42:26.752
The proof of which will be left
to the reader as an exercise.

00:42:26.752 --> 00:42:28.313
I hated when books said that.

00:42:28.313 --> 00:42:29.771
PROFESSOR: I actually
kind of think

00:42:29.771 --> 00:42:31.385
that's a proven
point, that you really

00:42:31.385 --> 00:42:34.719
should never trust output from
computer programs or packages--

00:42:34.719 --> 00:42:36.760
KENNETH ABBOTT: Or your
mother, or Mother Teresa.

