PROFESSOR: It's
good to check them.

00:42:38.218 --> 00:42:39.344
Check all the calculations.

00:42:39.344 --> 00:42:41.717
KENNETH ABBOTT: Mother Teresa
will slip you some bad data

00:42:41.717 --> 00:42:42.335
if she can.

00:42:42.335 --> 00:42:43.550
I'm telling you, she will.

00:42:43.550 --> 00:42:45.420
She's tricky that way.

00:42:45.420 --> 00:42:47.370
Don't trust anyone.

00:42:47.370 --> 00:42:51.010
I've caught mistakes
in software, all right?

00:42:51.010 --> 00:42:56.930
I had a programmer-- it's
one of my favorite stories--

00:42:56.930 --> 00:42:59.260
we're doing one of our first
Monte Carlo simulations,

00:42:59.260 --> 00:43:00.990
and we're factoring a matrix.

00:43:00.990 --> 00:43:05.640
If we have time, we'll get--
so I factor a covariance matrix

00:43:05.640 --> 00:43:13.900
into E transpose lambda E. It's
our friend the quadratic form.

00:43:13.900 --> 00:43:16.330
We're going to see this again.

00:43:16.330 --> 00:43:20.872
And this is a diagonal
matrix of eigenvalues.

00:43:20.872 --> 00:43:22.330
And I take the
square root of that.

00:43:22.330 --> 00:43:28.060
So I can say this is E transpose
lambda to the 1/2 lambda

00:43:28.060 --> 00:43:30.860
to the 1/2 E.

00:43:30.860 --> 00:43:33.850
And so my programmer had
gotten this, and I said,

00:43:33.850 --> 00:43:34.910
do me a favor.

00:43:34.910 --> 00:43:38.040
I said, take this, and transpose
and multiply by itself.

00:43:38.040 --> 00:43:39.730
So take the square
root and multiply it

00:43:39.730 --> 00:43:43.650
by the other square root, and
show me that you get this.

00:43:43.650 --> 00:43:44.410
Just show me.

00:43:44.410 --> 00:43:45.130
He said I got it.

00:43:45.130 --> 00:43:45.880
I said you got it?

00:43:45.880 --> 00:43:48.450
He said out to 16 decimals.

00:43:48.450 --> 00:43:50.510
I said stop.

00:43:50.510 --> 00:43:56.075
On my block, the square root
of 2 times the square root of 2

00:43:56.075 --> 00:43:58.820
equals 2.0.

00:43:58.820 --> 00:43:59.860
All right?

00:43:59.860 --> 00:44:04.470
2.0000000, what do you mean
out to 16 decimal places?

00:44:04.470 --> 00:44:06.980
What planet are you on?

00:44:06.980 --> 00:44:09.640
And I scratched the
surface, and I dug,

00:44:09.640 --> 00:44:11.570
and I asked a
bunch of questions.

00:44:11.570 --> 00:44:13.385
And it turned out
in this code he

00:44:13.385 --> 00:44:16.390
was passing a float to a fixed.

00:44:16.390 --> 00:44:17.760
All right?

00:44:17.760 --> 00:44:20.480
Don't trust anyone's software.

00:44:20.480 --> 00:44:21.330
Check it yourself.

00:44:24.690 --> 00:44:27.610
Someday when I'm dead and
you guys are in my position,

00:44:27.610 --> 00:44:29.880
you'll be thanking me for that.

00:44:29.880 --> 00:44:31.657
Put a stone on my
