All right.

00:45:26.030 --> 00:45:28.220
So more facts.

00:45:28.220 --> 00:45:31.030
Variance of xa
times yb; x squared

00:45:31.030 --> 00:45:35.467
variance a, y squared variance
b plus 2xy covariance ab.

00:45:35.467 --> 00:45:36.550
You guys seen this before?

00:45:36.550 --> 00:45:37.530
I assume you have.

00:45:40.240 --> 00:45:43.390
Now I can get pretty
silly with this if I want.

00:45:43.390 --> 00:45:46.970
x, a, y, b you get
the picture, right?

00:45:46.970 --> 00:45:51.160
But what you should
be thinking, this

00:45:51.160 --> 00:45:58.860
is a covariance matrix,
sigma squared, sigma squared,

00:45:58.860 --> 00:46:00.840
sigma squared.

00:46:00.840 --> 00:46:04.050
It's the sum of the variances
plus 2 times the sum

00:46:04.050 --> 00:46:05.500
of the covariances.

00:46:05.500 --> 00:46:09.100
So if I have one unit of every
asset, I've got n assets,

00:46:09.100 --> 00:46:12.300
all have to do to get the
portfolio variance is sum up

00:46:12.300 --> 00:46:13.890
the whole covariance matrix.

00:46:13.890 --> 00:46:16.700
Now, you never get only
one unit, but just saying.

00:46:16.700 --> 00:46:20.840
But you notice that this is
kind of a regular pattern

00:46:20.840 --> 00:46:22.770
that we see here.

00:46:22.770 --> 00:46:24.210
And so what I can
do is I can use

00:46:24.210 --> 00:46:27.230
a combination of my
correlation matrix

00:46:27.230 --> 00:46:31.180
and a little bit of linear
algebra legerdemain,

00:46:31.180 --> 00:46:33.330
to do some very
convenient calculations.

00:46:33.330 --> 00:46:35.580
And here I just give an
example of a covariance matrix

00:46:35.580 --> 00:46:37.060
and a correlation matrix.

00:46:37.060 --> 00:46:39.607
Note the correlation
matrices between negative 1

00:46:39.607 --> 00:46:41.430
and positive 1.

00:46:41.430 --> 00:46:41.930
All right.

00:46:44.932 --> 00:46:46.140
Let me cut to the chase here.

00:46:51.724 --> 00:46:53.140
I'll draw it here
because I really

00:46:53.140 --> 00:46:57.180
want to get into some
