01:01:45.970 --> 01:01:47.010
to that order statistic.

01:01:50.330 --> 01:01:52.026
Lends a lot more flexibility.

01:01:52.026 --> 01:01:54.400
So I can go and I can tweak
the way I do that simulation,

01:01:54.400 --> 01:01:56.145
I can relax my
assumptions of normality.

01:01:58.304 --> 01:01:59.970
I don't have to use
normal distribution,

01:01:59.970 --> 01:02:01.740
I could use a t distribution,
I could do lots,

01:02:01.740 --> 01:02:03.906
I could tweak my distribution,
I could customize it.

01:02:03.906 --> 01:02:06.150
I could put mean
reversion in there,

01:02:06.150 --> 01:02:08.410
I could do all kinds of stuff.

01:02:08.410 --> 01:02:12.300
So another way we do
value at risk is we

01:02:12.300 --> 01:02:15.110
simulate possible outcomes.

01:02:15.110 --> 01:02:19.670
We rank the outcomes,
and we just count them.

01:02:19.670 --> 01:02:21.763
If I've got the
10,000 observations

01:02:21.763 --> 01:02:23.240
and I want my 5%
order statistic,

01:02:23.240 --> 01:02:25.230
well I just take my 500th.

01:02:27.830 --> 01:02:28.820
Make sense?

01:02:28.820 --> 01:02:30.890
It's that simple.

01:02:30.890 --> 01:02:32.306
Well, I don't want
to make it seem

01:02:32.306 --> 01:02:33.200
like it's that simple
because it actually

01:02:33.200 --> 01:02:35.140
gets a little messy in here.

01:02:35.140 --> 01:02:37.680
But when we do Monte
Carlo simulation,

01:02:37.680 --> 01:02:40.449
we're simulating what we
think is going to happen

01:02:40.449 --> 01:02:41.740
all subject to our assumptions.

01:02:44.640 --> 01:02:46.880
And we run through this
Monte Carlo simulation.

01:02:46.880 --> 01:02:49.830
Simulation of method using
sequences of random numbers.

01:02:49.830 --> 01:02:51.550
Coined during the
Manhattan Project,

01:02:51.550 --> 01:02:54.430
similar to games of chance.

01:02:54.430 --> 01:02:57.610
You need to describe your system
in terms of probability density

01:02:57.610 --> 01:02:58.480
functions.

01:02:58.480 --> 01:03:00.900
What type of distribution?

01:03:00.900 --> 01:03:02.040
Is this normal?

01:03:02.040 --> 01:03:02.540
Is it t?

01:03:02.540 --> 01:03:03.470
Is it chi squared?

01:03:03.470 --> 01:03:04.500
Is it F?

01:03:04.500 --> 01:03:05.360
All right?

01:03:05.360 --> 01:03:07.800
That's the way we do it.

01:03:07.800 --> 01:03:09.720
So quickly, how do I do that?

01:03:14.570 --> 01:03:16.200
I have to have random numbers.

01:03:16.200 --> 01:03:19.760
Now they're truly
random numbers.

01:03:19.760 --> 01:03:22.457
Somewhere at MIT you could
buy-- I used to say tape,

01:03:22.457 --> 01:03:23.540
but people don't use tape.

01:03:23.540 --> 01:03:28.840
They'll give you a website where
you can get the atomic decay.

01:03:28.840 --> 01:03:30.450
That's random.

01:03:30.450 --> 01:03:31.706
All right?

01:03:31.706 --> 01:03:36.480
Anything else is pseudo-random.

01:03:36.480 --> 01:03:39.190
What you see when
you go into MATLAB,

01:03:39.190 --> 01:03:41.570
you have a random number
generator, it's an algorithm.

01:03:41.570 --> 01:03:45.110
It probably takes some number
and takes the square root

01:03:45.110 --> 01:03:47.910
of that number and then goes
54 decimal places to the right

01:03:47.910 --> 01:03:51.690
and takes the 55 decimal
places to the right,

01:03:51.690 --> 01:03:55.170
multiplies those
two numbers together

01:03:55.170 --> 01:03:58.110
and then takes the fifth root,
and then goes 16 decimal places

01:03:58.110 --> 01:04:01.610
to the right to get that--
it's some algorithm.

01:04:01.610 --> 01:04:05.590
True story, before I came to
appreciate that these were all

01:04:05.590 --> 01:04:09.225
highly algorithmically
driven, I was in my 20's, I

01:04:09.225 --> 01:04:11.390
was taking a computer
class, I saw two computers,

01:04:11.390 --> 01:04:13.830
