the same random numbers.

01:04:17.190 --> 01:04:19.870
And I thought I was
at the event horizon.

01:04:19.870 --> 01:04:22.760
I thought that light was
bending and the world

01:04:22.760 --> 01:04:24.610
was coming to an end, all right?

01:04:24.610 --> 01:04:27.767
Because this this stuff
can't happen, all right?

01:04:27.767 --> 01:04:29.350
It was happening
right in front of me.

01:04:29.350 --> 01:04:31.860
It was a pseudo-random
number generator.

01:04:31.860 --> 01:04:34.860
I didn't know, I was 24.

01:04:34.860 --> 01:04:35.360
Anyway.

01:04:38.320 --> 01:04:42.810
quasi-random numbers, it's sort
of a way of imposing some order

01:04:42.810 --> 01:04:43.790
on your random numbers.

01:04:43.790 --> 01:04:47.020
You random numbers, one
particular set of draws

01:04:47.020 --> 01:04:49.895
may not have enough draws
in a particular area

01:04:49.895 --> 01:04:51.270
to give you the
numbers you want.

01:04:51.270 --> 01:04:53.767
I can impose some
conditions upon that.

01:04:53.767 --> 01:04:56.100
I don't want to get into a
discussion of random numbers.

01:04:58.850 --> 01:05:02.250
How do I get from
random uniform--

01:05:02.250 --> 01:05:05.610
most random number generators
give you random uniform number

01:05:05.610 --> 01:05:07.280
between 0 and 1.

01:05:07.280 --> 01:05:10.080
What you'll typically do is
you'll take that random uniform

01:05:10.080 --> 01:05:13.190
number, you'll map it over
to the cumulative density

01:05:13.190 --> 01:05:16.340
function, and map it down.

01:05:16.340 --> 01:05:19.720
So this gets you from
random uniform space

01:05:19.720 --> 01:05:23.150
into standard deviation space.

01:05:23.150 --> 01:05:24.860
We used to worry
about how we did this,

01:05:24.860 --> 01:05:27.534
now your software
does it for you.

01:05:27.534 --> 01:05:29.450
I've gotten comfortable
enough, truth be told.

01:05:29.450 --> 01:05:36.040
I usually trust my random number
generators in Excel, in MATLAB.

01:05:36.040 --> 01:05:38.980
So I kind of violate my
