01:05:38.980 --> 01:05:43.940
But I think most of your
standard random number

01:05:43.940 --> 01:05:46.074
of generators are
decent enough now.

01:05:46.074 --> 01:05:47.490
And you can go
straight to normal,

01:05:47.490 --> 01:05:50.150
you don't have to do
random uniform and back

01:05:50.150 --> 01:05:51.280
into random normal.

01:05:51.280 --> 01:05:53.910
You can get it distributed
in any way you want.

01:05:59.550 --> 01:06:05.524
What I do when I do a Monte
Carlo simulation-- and this

01:06:05.524 --> 01:06:08.065
is going to be rushed because
we've only got like 20 minutes.

01:06:10.800 --> 01:06:14.165
If I take a covariance
matrix-- you're

01:06:14.165 --> 01:06:15.540
going to have to
trust me on this

01:06:15.540 --> 01:06:18.460
because again, I'm covering
like eight hours of lecture

01:06:18.460 --> 01:06:19.907
in an hour and a half.

01:06:19.907 --> 01:06:21.740
You guys go to MIT so
I have no doubt you're

01:06:21.740 --> 01:06:22.823
going to be all over this.

01:06:48.134 --> 01:06:52.080
Let's take this out
of here for a second.

01:06:52.080 --> 01:06:56.250
I can factor my
covariance structure.

01:06:59.070 --> 01:07:02.716
I can factor my covariance
structure like this.

01:07:02.716 --> 01:07:05.300
And this is the
transpose of this.

01:07:05.300 --> 01:07:08.920
I didn't realize that the first
time we did this commercially

01:07:08.920 --> 01:07:12.690
I saw this instead of
this and I thought we had

01:07:12.690 --> 01:07:13.940
sent bad data to the customer.

01:07:13.940 --> 01:07:15.280
I got physically sick.

01:07:15.280 --> 01:07:21.190
And then I remembered
AB transpose

01:07:21.190 --> 01:07:25.840
equals B transpose A--
these things keep happening.

01:07:25.840 --> 01:07:28.720
My high school math
keeps coming back to me.

01:07:28.720 --> 01:07:31.114
But I had forgotten this
and I got physically sick

01:07:31.114 --> 01:07:33.030
because I thought we'd
sent bad data because I

01:07:33.030 --> 01:07:36.400
was looking at this when it's
just the transpose of this.

01:07:36.400 --> 01:07:39.900
Anyway, I can factor
this into this where this

01:07:39.900 --> 01:07:44.550
is a matrix of eigenvectors.

01:07:44.550 --> 01:07:48.195
This is a diagonal matrix
of the eigenvalues.

01:07:48.195 --> 01:07:50.640
All right?

01:07:50.640 --> 01:07:56.100
This is the vaunted
Gaussian copula.

01:07:56.100 --> 01:07:57.930
This is it.

01:07:57.930 --> 01:07:59.560
Most people view
it as a black box.

01:07:59.560 --> 01:08:01.890
If you've had any more than
introductory statistics,

01:08:01.890 --> 01:08:03.360
this should be a
glass box to you.

01:08:03.360 --> 01:08:04.765
That's why I wanted to go
through this even though I'd

01:08:04.765 --> 01:08:07.872
love to spend another hour and
a half and do about 50 examples.

01:08:07.872 --> 01:08:09.330
Because this is
how I learned this,

01:08:09.330 --> 01:08:12.880
I didn't learn it from looking
at this equation and saying,

01:08:12.880 --> 01:08:13.530
oh, I get it.

01:08:13.530 --> 01:08:15.870
I learned it from actually
doing it about 1,000 times

01:08:15.870 --> 01:08:20.020
in a spreadsheet, and sunk
in like water into a stone.

01:08:20.020 --> 01:08:23.649
So I factor this
matrix, and then

01:08:23.649 --> 01:08:33.250
I take this, which is the
square root matrix, which

01:08:33.250 --> 01:08:36.020
is my transpose of
my eigenvector matrix

01:08:36.020 --> 01:08:39.490
and diagonal matrix contain the
square root of my eigenvalues.

01:08:39.490 --> 01:08:42.750
Now, could this ever
be negative and take me

01:08:42.750 --> 01:08:44.910
into imaginary root land?

01:08:44.910 --> 01:08:50.140
Well, if my variances
are positive or zero,

01:08:50.140 --> 01:08:52.176
then that will be a problem.

01:08:52.176 --> 01:08:53.800
So here we get into
this-- remember you

01:08:53.800 --> 01:08:55.899
guys studied positive
semidefinite,

01:08:55.899 --> 01:08:56.649
positive definite.

01:08:56.649 --> 01:08:59.232
Once again, it's another one of
these high school math things.

01:08:59.232 --> 01:09:00.130
Like, here it is.

01:09:00.130 --> 01:09:02.035
I had to know this.

01:09:02.035 --> 01:09:04.160
Suddenly I care whether
it's positive semidefinite.

01:09:04.160 --> 01:09:08.270
Covariance structures have
to be positive semidefinite.

01:09:08.270 --> 01:09:10.450
If you don't have a
complete data set,

01:09:10.450 --> 01:09:13.439
let's say you've got 100
observations, 100 observations,

01:09:13.439 --> 01:09:17.740
100 observations, 25
observations, 100 observations,

01:09:17.740 --> 01:09:19.486
you may have a
negative eigenvalue.

01:09:19.486 --> 01:09:21.569
If you just measure the
covariance with the amount

01:09:21.569 --> 01:09:23.160
of data that you have.

01:09:23.160 --> 01:09:26.430
My intuition-- and I doubt
this is the [INAUDIBLE]--

01:09:26.430 --> 01:09:28.880
is that you're measuring
with error and you have fewer

01:09:28.880 --> 01:09:31.470
observations you
measure with more error.

01:09:31.470 --> 01:09:35.160
So it's possible if some
of your covariance measures

01:09:35.160 --> 01:09:38.000
have 25 observations
and some of them

01:09:38.000 --> 01:09:41.590
have 100 observations that
there's more error in some

01:09:41.590 --> 01:09:42.229
than in others.

01:09:42.229 --> 01:09:44.529
And so there's the
theoretical possibility

01:09:44.529 --> 01:09:46.550
for negative variance.

01:09:46.550 --> 01:09:51.060
True story, we didn't
know this in the '90s.

01:09:51.060 --> 01:09:54.075
I took this problem to the
chairman of the statistics

01:09:54.075 --> 01:09:58.290
department at NYU said, I'm
getting negative eigenvalues.

01:09:58.290 --> 01:10:00.140
And he didn't know.

01:10:00.140 --> 01:10:03.370
He had no idea,
he's a smart guy.

01:10:03.370 --> 01:10:06.260
You have to fill in
your missing data.

01:10:06.260 --> 01:10:08.500
You have to fill in
your missing data.

01:10:08.500 --> 01:10:10.500
If you've got 1,000
observations, 1,000

01:10:10.500 --> 01:10:12.654
observations, 1,000
observations, 200 observations,

01:10:12.654 --> 01:10:14.320
and you want to make
sure you won't have

01:10:14.320 --> 01:10:16.300
