01:16:14.450 --> 01:16:22.370
What I did was I happened to
generate 1,000 samples here.

01:16:22.370 --> 01:16:25.530
But I could generate
10,000 or 100,000,

01:16:25.530 --> 01:16:27.740
or a million or 10
million or a billion

01:16:27.740 --> 01:16:29.570
just by doing more
random normals.

01:16:29.570 --> 01:16:31.640
I could generate--
in effect, what

01:16:31.640 --> 01:16:36.695
I'm generating here is
synthetic time series that

01:16:36.695 --> 01:16:39.680
have properties similar
to my underlying data.

01:16:42.250 --> 01:16:44.430
That's what Monte Carlo
simulation is about.

01:16:44.430 --> 01:16:48.100
The means and the variances and
the covariances of this data

01:16:48.100 --> 01:16:50.470
set are just like that.

01:16:50.470 --> 01:16:53.700
Now, again, true story, when
somebody first showed me this

01:16:53.700 --> 01:16:54.680
I did not believe them.

01:16:54.680 --> 01:16:58.346
So I developed a
bunch of little tests.

01:16:58.346 --> 01:17:02.210
And I said, let me just look
at the correlation of my Monte

01:17:02.210 --> 01:17:07.430
Carlo data versus my
original correlation matrix.

01:17:07.430 --> 01:17:13.270
So 0.83, 0.84, 0.85,
0.85, 0.67, 0.81.

01:17:13.270 --> 01:17:16.510
You look at the corresponding
ones of the random numbers I

01:17:16.510 --> 01:17:21.890
just generated, 0.81, 0.82,
0.84, 0.84, 0.64, 0.52.

01:17:21.890 --> 01:17:24.641
0.54 versus 0.52.

01:17:24.641 --> 01:17:26.580
0.18 Versus 0.12.

01:17:26.580 --> 01:17:28.600
0.51 versus 0.47.

01:17:28.600 --> 01:17:32.270
Somebody want to tell me
why they're not spot on?

01:17:32.270 --> 01:17:34.150
Sampling error.

01:17:34.150 --> 01:17:37.270
The more data I use the
closer it will get to that.

01:17:37.270 --> 01:17:41.290
If I do 1 million, I'd better
get right on top of that.

01:17:41.290 --> 01:17:43.450
Does that make sense?

01:17:43.450 --> 01:17:46.490
So what I'm telling
you here is that I can

01:17:46.490 --> 01:17:48.080
generate synthetic time series.

01:17:48.080 --> 01:17:49.559
Now, why would I
generate so many?

01:17:49.559 --> 01:17:51.100
Well because,
remember, I care what's

01:17:51.100 --> 01:17:53.260
going on out in that tail.

01:17:53.260 --> 01:17:56.220
If I only have 100 observations
and I'm looking empirically

01:17:56.220 --> 01:18:01.040
at my tail, I've only got one
observation out in the 1% tail.

01:18:01.040 --> 01:18:04.040
And that doesn't tell me a
whole lot about what's going on.

01:18:04.040 --> 01:18:06.100
If I can simulate that
distribution exactly,

01:18:06.100 --> 01:18:08.635
I can say, you know what, I
want a billion observations

01:18:08.635 --> 01:18:10.740
in that tail.

01:18:10.740 --> 01:18:12.000
Now we can look at that tail.

01:18:18.506 --> 01:18:19.880
If I have 1 billion
observations,

01:18:19.880 --> 01:18:22.750
let's say I'm looking at some
kind of normal distribution.

01:18:22.750 --> 01:18:27.200
I'm circling it out
here, I'm seeing--

01:18:27.200 --> 01:18:29.930
I can really dig in and see what
the properties of this thing

01:18:29.930 --> 01:18:30.560
are.

01:18:30.560 --> 01:18:32.980
In fact, this can really
only take two distributions,

01:18:32.980 --> 01:18:34.063
and really, it's only one.

01:18:34.063 --> 01:18:36.870
But that's another story.

01:18:36.870 --> 01:18:39.210
So what I do in Monte
Carlo simulations,

01:18:39.210 --> 01:18:45.800
I'm simulating these outcomes
so we can get a lot more meat

01:18:45.800 --> 01:18:48.419
in this tail to understand
what's happening out there.

01:18:48.419 --> 01:18:49.460
Does it drop off quickly?

01:18:49.460 --> 01:18:50.970
Does it not drop off quickly?

01:18:50.970 --> 01:18:53.920
That's kind of what it's about.

